	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />No and the alternatives are EEPROM and FlashROM or battery backed SRAM. I would choose EEPROM over flash or SRAM.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Bregalad</b> [ Mon Oct 02, 2006 11:14 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Battery backed SRAM ??
<br />Not only normal NES boards doesn't have a slot for battery, but also all games that want to write to the mapper will ERASE rom data.
<br />It would only go for board with bus conflicts, and those doesn't have battery.
<br />
<br />Also, I cannot find any existing EEPROM above the 28C256 (32kbx8).
<br />Flashrom has different pinout so a lot of rewiring is needed.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Memblers</b> [ Mon Oct 02, 2006 12:03 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Battery backed SRAM ??<br />Not only normal NES boards doesn't have a slot for battery, but also all games that want to write to the mapper will ERASE rom data.<br /></div>
<br />
<br />There are chips like the Dallas DS1245 that are SRAM with an internal battery and power monitor.  But I think it'd be almost absurd to use it, unless you want NVRAM to write to.  Those chips are physically huge and fairly expensive.
<br />
<br />It's easy to prevent a write though, just don't hook memory up to the /write line.  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_smile.gif" alt=":)" title="Smile" />
<br />
<br />I'd say to go with FlashROM though.  You can get up to 512kB, 29F040 or 29C040.  And 29C256 if you want 32kB (no rewiring needed for that one).

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


